AUDIO: 'Fine-tuning a 12-billion parameter model on your own machine usually ends one way. A CUDA out of memory crash. But what if you could do it on a laptop with just 8 GB? Akshay Pacha showed exactly that. And Google\'s own Gemma account reshared'

[00:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it. Before fine-tuning, the model guesses random chess moves. After it finds the exact missing move. So, can a model this small really learn that? Let\'s walk through Akshay\'s build step'

[00:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'by step. First, the model. Akshay uses Gemma 4, the 12-billion parameter version. It is multimodal. It handles text, images, and audio. And it runs on just 8 GB of memory.'

[00:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The goal he set is sharp. Give the model a chess game with one move missing plus the final result. It has to predict the exact move that is gone. Random guessing will not cut it.'

[00:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The model has to actually understand the board. The whole build is six moves. Load the model. Define the LoRA config. Load the data set.'

[01:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Build the trainer. Train it, then test before and after. Two tools carried the project. Unsloth for efficient fine-tuning. And Hugging Face Transformers to run everything locally. No cloud, no giant GPU.'

[01:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Here is step one. Step one, load the model. Akshay loads Gemma 4 and its tokenizer using Unsloth. One call pulls the model down and gets it ready in memory. This is the part people think needs a'

[01:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'data center. It does not. It fits in 8 GB. Step two, the LoRA config. This is the trick that makes 8 GB enough. Instead of retraining all 12-billion'

[01:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'parameters, LoRA trains a tiny set of new ones. Akshay uses Unsloth\'s PEFT helper. He picks the rank and which layers to fine-tune. The language layers and the attention modules. Small footprint.'

[01:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Real learning. Step three, the data. He uses the chess instruct data set from hugging face. Each example is a chess game with one move removed plus the final result. Then he standardizes it into a'

[02:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'conversation format, so Gemma can train on it. The data is the teacher here. Step four, the trainer. Akshay sets the training config. The learning rate, the model, the'

[02:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'tokenizer. Then he hits go. Watch the logs. The loss drops as the steps climb. That falling number is the model actually learning the game. This is the moment a random guesser'

[02:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'becomes a chess player. So, did it work? Here is the test. Before fine-tuning, the model generates random chess moves. Junk. After fine-tuning on the same prompt, it finds the exact missing move.'

[02:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Same model. Same 8 GB. The only thing that changed was Akshay\'s training run. That is the whole point of fine-tuning. You teach a general model one specific'

